description._value: Several xylem-associated regulatory genes have been identified that control processes associated with wood formation in poplar. Prominent among these are the NAC domain transcription factors (NACs). We evaluated the putative involvement of Populus NAC154, a co-ortholog of the Arabidopsis gene SND2, as a regulator of secondary biosynthetic processes in stem internode tissues by interrogating methanol:water extracts from control and transgenic trees. Comprehensive untargeted metabolite profiling was accomplished with a liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry platform that utilized two different chromatographic supports (HILIC and reversed phase) and both positive and negative ionization modes. Evaluation of current and previous year tissues provided datasets for assessing the effects of NAC154 overexpression in wood maturation processes. Phenolic glycoside levels as well as those of oligolignols, sucrose and arginine were modulated with phenotypic and chemotypic traits exhibiting similar trends. Specifically, increased levels of arginine in the NAC154 overexpressing tissues supports a role for the transcription factor in senescence/dormancy-associated processes.

authorList._value: Amy M. Brunner and Richard F. Helm

title._value: A metabolomic assessment of NAC154 transcription factor overexpression in field grown poplar stem wood

value._value: Populus tremula x Populus alba clone 717-1B4

description._value: Samples were collected from the field according to the leaf plastochron index (LPI), tagged and frozen in dry ice.  For current year shoot segments, we defined LPI 1 as the first leaf below the shoot tip that was at least 1 cm in length (internode 1 would be directly above this), and counted down to collect internode 12.  For the previous year growth, internode 1 was assigned as below the terminal bud scar, counting down the stem to internode 7.   Since trees showed different amounts of growth (number of internodes) in a given year, a continuous internode counting down from the shoot tip to the previous year's growth was not applicable.  Samples in the laboratory were stored at -80 °C prior to processing, which was initiated by freeze-drying to a constant weight.  Twigs were flash frozen in liquid nitrogen and subsequently ground in a P14 mill (Pulveristette 14; Fritsch) with a 0.5 mm sieve at maximum speed (20,000 rpm) to generate a fine powder.  The samples were collected in labeled, pre-weighed 1.5 ml centrifuge tubes, flash frozen in liquid nitrogen and dried, after which the mass was recorded.

Sample extraction was performed on 10 mg fractions using (50:50 LCMS grade MeOH:H2O, 1 ml).  The tube contents were mixed by vortexing, placed in a shaker (Boekel Sci; Feasterville, PA) and incubated 200 minutes at 30 °C.  The tubes were then removed, vortexed briefly and allowed to sit overnight at room temperature.  The samples were then vortexed and centrifuged (13,000 x g, 5 min, RT) with the extracts (450 µl) transferred to prelabeled, ethanol-washed tubes.  The samples were then concentrated via centrifugal concentration until approximately 200 µl remained and were then flash frozen in liquid nitrogen and dried overnight on high vacuum line with liquid nitrogen trap.   The resulting dried extract was then weighed to determined yield.

Reversed-phase Separations.</br>
The extract was reconstituted with 50 nM acetaminophen (internal standard) in 0.1% aq. formic acid:acetonitrile (9:1, v/v) with the volume based upon the weight of the dried extract (100 µl/mg dry extract). Dissolution was aided by vortexing followed by sonication (10 min).  The samples were then centrifuged (13,000 x g; 10 min; RT) and an aliquot was removed (100 µl) making sure not to disturb any precipitate.  The sample was further diluted (10x) with 50 nM  acetaminophen in 0.1% formic acid:acetonitrile (9:1, v/v) and transferred to a LC-MS grade autosampler vial.  A MasterMix" was constructed from a single representative sample from each class. This sample is used to equilibrate the LC-MS system and is also used for statistical validation.
